  "prompt": "Why is M&M's motto \"melts in your mouth, not in your hand\"?",
  "response": "M&M's motto, \"Melts in your mouth, not in your hand,\" was introduced in the 1950s and has since become one of the most recognizable slogans in advertising history. The phrase highlights the unique selling point of M&M's candy: their **hard candy shell** that prevents the chocolate from melting too quickly.\n\nHere\u2019s why this motto is so effective:\n\n1. **The Hard Shell Innovation**: M&M's were originally created to allow chocolate to be enjoyed without melting in warm conditions (a problem for other chocolates). The sugar shell acts as a protective barrier, keeping the chocolate intact until it\u2019s eaten.\n\n2. **Mess-Free Eating**: The slogan emphasizes convenience\u2014M&M's won\u2019t leave chocolate residue on your hands, making them a clean and practical snack.\n\n3. **Memorable and Relatable**: The phrase is catchy, easy to remember, and directly addresses a common frustration people have with chocolate: the mess it can create.\n\n4. **Brand Identity**: Over time, the motto has become synonymous with M&M's, reinforcing their brand image as a fun, dependable, and enjoyable treat.\n\nOverall, the slogan cleverly combines M&M's functional benefit with a promise of enjoyment, making it a cornerstone of their marketing for decades.",
